00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:14.090
in your previous books that you
wished you could have left it?

00:26:14.090 --> 00:26:15.520
&gt;&gt; Kiersten White:
That's a good question.

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:21.770
I think I end up feeling like
if I have to take something

00:26:21.770 --> 00:26:23.240 position:56%
out there's a reason to take it out.

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:25.320
So people will ask, "are
there deleted scene?"

00:26:25.320 --> 00:26:27.840
Yeah, but if they're deleted
there's a reason for that.

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:29.970
My best example of that
was actually Paranormalcy,

00:26:29.970 --> 00:26:33.360
which is my first book,
and I ended up cutting

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:37.130
about forty pages before
I sent it out to editors.

00:26:37.130 --> 00:26:40.750
And one of the scenes was this
day when Evie goes to high school

00:26:40.750 --> 00:26:43.810
and it was adorable and she got
to go to high school and she got

00:26:43.810 --> 00:26:46.920
to make all of these jokes
relating it to teen dramas on TV

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:49.590
and it just kind of
went on and on and on

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:52.360
because I was having fun writing it
and I was having fun giving her all

00:26:52.360 --> 00:26:55.670
of those experiences, but what
it did was it dragged the plot

00:26:55.670 --> 00:26:58.290
to a standstill and it sucked all

00:26:58.290 --> 00:27:00.390
of the narrative tension
out of the book.

00:27:00.390 --> 00:27:02.750
And so my friend and critique
partner Stephanie Perkins,

00:27:02.750 --> 00:27:05.730
who is brilliant, said, "This
doesn't need to be here."

00:27:05.730 --> 00:27:07.720
And at first I was like,
"No, but I love it so much."

00:27:07.720 --> 00:27:10.430
And then I realized OK it
doesn't need to be here.

00:27:10.430 --> 00:27:11.860
And those things that I
loved so much about it

00:27:11.860 --> 00:27:14.890
like that really good joke or this
fun scene I could actually pull

00:27:14.890 --> 00:27:16.900
out and put in other places.

00:27:16.900 --> 00:27:19.930
So out of the fifteen pages, there
were really only a few paragraphs

00:27:19.930 --> 00:27:23.100
that I loved so much and I
used them somewhere else.

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:27.450
So for me the editorial process is
just as important as the drafting

00:27:27.450 --> 00:27:31.200
because the drafting gets
the story on the paper.

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:33.520
I would say stories are
made in the first draft,

00:27:33.520 --> 00:27:34.870
books are made in editing.

00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:39.790
So I never get too attached and
often times I forget what I cut

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:41.390
because it's not essential
to the story.

00:27:41.390 --> 00:27:42.690
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible].

00:27:42.690 --> 00:27:44.960
&gt;&gt; Kiersten White:
And editors are great.

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:46.880
Editors are so smart you guys.

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:49.550
Editors are the best because
they can look at what you made

00:27:49.550 --> 00:27:51.430
and say, "This is so good.

00:27:51.430 --> 00:27:52.730
I love this so much.

00:27:52.730 --> 00:27:54.030
Here's ten pages on
what you need to fix."

00:27:54.030 --> 00:27:55.330
[ Laughter ]

00:27:55.330 --> 00:27:57.520
And you're like, "OK."

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:01.050
But then they're right
on everything, so yeah.

00:28:01.050 --> 00:28:03.720
I've had people ask if I
would ever self-publish

00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:07.010
because I have several manuscripts
that I've written completely

00:28:07.010 --> 00:28:10.120
and that didn't for whatever
reason get published and I say no

00:28:10.120 --> 00:28:15.740 position:56%
because I don't want to put out
anything that's not my absolute best

00:28:15.740 --> 00:28:18.940
and I feel that editors make my
stuff [phonetic] my absolute best,

00:28:18.940 --> 00:28:22.150
so it's important to
me to go through that.

