00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:27.680
such an interesting and fraught
and rewarding relationship,

00:29:27.680 --> 00:29:30.440
so I really like writing those.

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:31.740
&gt;&gt; Hi.

00:29:31.740 --> 00:29:33.040
&gt;&gt; Kiersten White: Hi.

00:29:33.040 --> 00:29:34.340
&gt;&gt; I have two questions.

00:29:34.340 --> 00:29:35.640
&gt;&gt; Kiersten White: OK.

00:29:35.640 --> 00:29:36.960
&gt;&gt; My first is, and you
must get this a lot,

00:29:36.960 --> 00:29:40.590
not every aspiring writer is
going to get their first book

00:29:40.590 --> 00:29:41.890
and it's going to be really good.

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:44.340
What would you suggest,
like any tips,

00:29:44.340 --> 00:29:46.650
if you wanted to become a
writer, but you're not sure?

00:29:46.650 --> 00:29:48.500
&gt;&gt; Kiersten White: Yeah,
well my first book that came

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:50.810
out was not my first book,
it was my fourth book,

00:29:50.810 --> 00:29:52.770
so that right there, you know?

00:29:52.770 --> 00:29:54.070
It takes a while.

00:29:54.070 --> 00:29:56.600
So my advice if you want
to be a writer is to read.

00:29:56.600 --> 00:30:01.600
Read very widely, read what's
popular, read classics,

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:04.520
and look at it while you're
reading it, really pay attention.

00:30:04.520 --> 00:30:06.770
If you can't put it down,
what is the author doing

00:30:06.770 --> 00:30:08.930
that is engaging your
interest so much?

00:30:08.930 --> 00:30:10.650
And if you get bored and
you're losing interest,

00:30:10.650 --> 00:30:12.760
what has the author done
that has let you say, "Meh.

00:30:12.760 --> 00:30:15.080
I don't really want to keep
reading this anymore."?

00:30:15.080 --> 00:30:17.030
Because reading is
really the best education

00:30:17.030 --> 00:30:18.380
in writing that you can get.

00:30:18.380 --> 00:30:20.690
And then as far as
trying to get published,

00:30:20.690 --> 00:30:23.080
it really is just a
matter of doing the work,

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:26.550 position:56%
of sitting down finishing the draft,
editing it, getting it as best

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:31.370
as you can, and then sending it out
there and starting the next thing.

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:34.050
I actually started writing
Paranormalcy when another book

00:30:34.050 --> 00:30:36.480
of mine was on submission to
editors, and nobody bought that.

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:38.200
It's not a really fun way to do it.

00:30:38.200 --> 00:30:40.070
By the way, I really recommend
selling a book instead

00:30:40.070 --> 00:30:42.450
of not selling a book,
its way more fun.

00:30:42.450 --> 00:30:45.470
But in the meantime I had
been writing Paranormalcy,

00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:48.160
so when it was very clear that
first book wasn't going to sell,

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:51.130
I had something else
and I had something else

00:30:51.130 --> 00:30:52.760 position:56%
to give my agent and to go out with.

00:30:52.760 --> 00:30:55.780
And I didn't get an agent
right off the bat either,

00:30:55.780 --> 00:30:59.100
it took fifty letters, inquiry
letters you write to an agent

00:30:59.100 --> 00:31:00.890
and you say, "Hey, I wrote this
book, do you want to read it?"

00:31:00.890 --> 00:31:04.000
And they write back and say no
or they don't write back at all.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.810
So it took me fifty of
those to get an agent.

00:31:06.810 --> 00:31:10.830 position:56%
And then it took me my fourth book
to get published, so I say just keep

00:31:10.830 --> 00:31:13.830
at it, that's really the best thing
you can do is just keep writing.

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:17.070
And we're actually out of
time, but keep writing, OK?

00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:18.370
It's worth it.

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:19.670
And everything you
write you learn from,

00:31:19.670 --> 00:31:21.130
there's no writing that's wasted.

